<TEXT>
president bush appears to be weathering the 
first crisis of his presidency without jeopardizing his honeymoon 
with congress 
bush had warned that any proposal he devised for bailing out 
insolvent savings and loan institutions would not be popular 
but the plan he outlined monday is winning respect if not enthusiasm 
from democrats and republicans 
now that the first concrete legislative proposal to issue from 
the bush administration has given the president a chance to prove 
his leadership attention shifts to the larger challenge his budget 
address to congress on thursday 
were still waiting for the other shoe to drop said norman 
ornstein a political analyst at the conservative american 
enterprise institute so much is going to revolve around the 
budget that right now it is more of a test 
bushs bailout announced after consultation with top financial 
aides and leading members of congress calls for increased insurance 
fees on banks and savings and loans and the issuance of 50 billion 
in special bonds to finance the cost of failing institutions 
absent is a controversial earlier proposal the administration 
floated for a direct fee on depositors 
however when pressed on the subject at a news conference bush 
conceded there was no way of guaranteeing that the insurance 
increase wouldnt be passed along to depositors 
nothing is without pain when you come to solve a problem of 
this magnitude bush said 
his plan also would increase the justice departments budget by 
50 million to seek out and punish those whose mismanagement of 
sampls bush blamed for much of the problem 
bushs plan according to some analysts was a relatively 
skillful recovery from the awkwardness two weeks ago when his 
administrations consideration of a direct fee on depositors became 
known 
a firestorm of criticism followed both on capitol hill and from 
the industry and the criticism did not abate after some top 
administration officials including chief of staff john sununu kept 
the controversy simmering by suggesting publicly that the fee 
remained a live option 
steve hess an analyst on the presidency at the brookings 
institute a liberal research organization said bushs 
selfproclaimed decision to face the problem squarely even 
before his budget speech was an effort to regroup 
it wouldnt have happened had not his administration bungled it 
last week hess said 
still hess said bushs relations with congress remain good but 
theres always a honeymoon when theres nothing on the table he 
said it may end up as a twoweek honeymoon 
bush called his proposal the fairest system that the best minds 
in this administration can come up with 
but by including congressional budget leaders early on in the 
process of developing the scheme bush gave the first solid evidence 
of his inaugural address vow to extend an offered hand to 
congress 
and for that gesture members of both parties voiced their 
appreciation 
i think the proposal is by and large a sensible proposal 
said sen donald w riegle dmich chairman of the senate banking 
committee 
rep trent lott rmiss predicted the major portion of it 
will fly 
and sen phil gramm rtexas exclaimed i think youre going 
to see some real bipartisanship here 
but gramm added that even though he supported the presidents 
approach any answer to a multibilliondollar problem wasnt 
something youd want to embrace and kiss on the mouth 
we have a big selling job bush conceded on monday 
