<TEXT>
interest rates on shortterm treasury 
securities rose in the latest auction to the highest level in nearly 
four years 
the treasury department sold 72 billion in threemonth bills 
monday at an average discount rate of 857 percent up from 833 
percent last week another 72 billion was sold in sixmonth bills 
at an average discount rate of 853 percent up from 839 percent 
last week 
the rates were the highest since march 18 1985 when threemonth 
bills sold for 864 percent and april 8 1985 when sixmonth bills 
averaged 856 percent 
the new discount rates understate the actual return to investors 
888 percent for threemonth bills with a 10000 bill selling for 
978340 and 904 percent for a sixmonth bill selling for 
956880 
in a separate report the federal reserve said monday that the 
average yield for oneyear treasury bills the most popular index 
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages rose to 905 percent 
last week up from 897 percent the previous week 
