<DOCNO> AP890207-0034 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
to help take themselves off the hot seat on the 
pay issue congress in 1967 established a ninemember commission on 
executive legislative and judicial salaries 
the commissions job is to recommend to the president every four 
years the appropriate pay levels for members of the house and 
senate federal judges the president and vice president and the 
top layers of executivebranch workers 
three members of the panel are appointed by the president two by 
the president of the senate two by the speaker of the house and two 
by the chief justice their recommendations could be accepted 
rejected or modified by the president who then includes his final 
recommendations in the budget he submits to congress 
under the procedure unless both the house and senate vote to 
head them off the recommended raises become law 30 days after the 
president proposes them 
this years recommendations for a 51 percent pay raise for 
members of congress and similar increases for other top federal 
workers came from a commission chaired by lloyd cutler a 
washington attorney and former white house counsel to president 
carter 
