<TEXT>
barbara tuchman was remembered upon her 
death as the popular historian whose 1962 the guns of august 
reminded the superpowers of the dangers of diplomatic miscalculation 
as they teetered on the brink 
the twotime pulitzer prize winner and author of 11 books 
including the current best seller the first salute died monday 
at a hospital in greenwich following a stroke she was 77 
the guns of august had a tremendous impact on president 
kennedy and all who went through the cuban missile crisis said 
william manchester author of the death of a president and 
writerinresidence at wesleyan university in middletown 
tuchmans the first salute a look at the american revolution 
and the dutch revolution that preceded it by 200 years has been on 
the new york times bestseller list for 17 weeks 
she said last fall it would be her last book because of failing 
eyesight 
tuchman won the pulitzer for history for the guns of august 
in 1962 and stilwell and the american experience in china in 
1971 the latter work was hailed as brilliant by americas 
preeminent china scholar john k fairbank of harvard university 
in 1978 she was awarded the gold medal for history of the 
american academy and institute of arts and letters 
she also wrote the proud tower a story of europe before 
world war i and a distant mirror the calamitous 14th century 
which traces the tumult of the period by following the career of a 
feudal lord 
the guns of august which established her reputation 
examined how the military buildup in europe led the great powers to 
bungle their way into world war i 
it was a favorite of president kennedy because of its lessons for 
leaders in the nuclear age said historian arthur schlesinger jr a 
kennedy adviser kennedy presented a copy of the book to british 
prime minister harold macmillan 
what he felt was that the guns of august was a clear 
demonstration of the extent that miscalculation got people into 
war schlesinger said in a telephone interview 
writer john hersey who worked with tuchman on the issues of 
censorship and freedom of speech for the authors league called the 
book a kind of parable for our times to make us realize where 
some of our policies might lead us 
tuchman was born jan 30 1912 in new york city and graduated 
from radcliffe college in 1933 she lived in greenwich 
she expressed pride in the fact that she never gained an advanced 
degree and was not an academic saying during an interview last fall 
that a phd would have ruined me 
although some professional historians criticized some of her work 
as shallow others praised her as a writer whose broad scope and 
lively style made history exciting for the general reading public 
the guns of august was a superb book said john m blum 
sterling professor of history at yale university it would have 
been a very picayune professional historian who had any objections 
to it 
as an historian i belong to the how rather than the why 
school tuchman wrote in an autobiographical sketch i am a 
seeker of the small facts not the big explanation a narrator not a 
philosopher 
with each book i approached nearer as i hope to my goal of 
presenting history as literature 
tuchman began her career as an editorial assistant and occasional 
correspondent for the nation which her father investment banker 
maurice wertheim bought in 1935 to save from bankruptcy she 
covered president roosevelts 1936 campaign and the spanish civil 
war 
tuchmans mother alma morgenthau was a sister of henry 
morgenthau jr treasury secretary under president franklin d 
roosevelt 
during world war ii she worked for the us office of war 
information in new york 
tuchman is survived by her husband of 48 years dr lester r 
tuchman their three daughters a sister and four grandchildren 
a private funeral will be held wednesday a public memorial 
service will be held sunday at the new york city librarys celeste 
bartos forum 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

