<TEXT>
some notsowild turkeys have been making 
nuisances of themselves in suburban communities near plymouth rock 
perching on cars and taking over birdfeeders state wildlife 
officials said tuesday 
some of the big birds have been spotted wandering down streets 
and even have chased people in parts of plymouth and bristol 
counties according to james cardoza head of the states wild 
turkey restoration project 
richard turner who works for the state division of fisheries and 
wildlife at its bourne office said he received a complaint from the 
owner of a mercedes benz who was not happy to find a turkey 
trotting over the hood and roof of his expensive car last year he 
came across a turkey hen nesting in a mobile home park undisturbed 
by the urban setting 
turner said in a telephone interview tuesday that the birds are 
apparently penraised wild turkeys that have been freed and dont 
have the wily instincts of their truly wild counterparts he said he 
did not know how many might be loose in the two counties 
although it is illegal to keep wild turkeys in massachusetts 
turner said chicks are sometimes sold at county fairs and 
unsuspecting people have bought them thinking it would be nice to 
have some wild turkeys in their yard 
the problem according to the biologists is that the penreared 
turkeys could interbreed with and dilute the stocks of wild turkeys 
the state is trying to reintroduce to the area south of boston 
they also could introduce disease 
james baird natural history director for the massachusetts 
audubon society said he was not familiar with the turkey problem 
but he noted that it is not uncommon to see ringnecked 
pheasants lose of the reticence of wild birds when they have been 
penraised and then released into the wild 
often they wind up standing by the side of the road wondering 
what to do next baird said birds do become habituated to a 
human presence as long as it is nonthreatening and they are liable 
to turn up anywhere they can find food 
the states wild turkey restoration effort began in 1972 with the 
release of a few pairs of wild birds captured in new york state 
since then the number of wild turkeys in the berkshires the states 
western mountains has grown to about 5000 
since 1979 the state has helping them spread east through the 
state by trapping and relocating birds from the berkshires 
for the past nine years the birds have been numerous enough in 
some areas to allow hunting last year hunters bagged a record 471 
birds most in western massachusetts 
</TEXT>
