<TEXT>
a un panel on tuesday launched an 18month study 
on the risk of climate changes including global warming and rising 
sea levels that have been linked to atmospheric pollution 
the chairman swedish meteorology professor bert bolin called on 
governments for early action to prevent a crisis 
the study will gather data on climate change and its possible 
effects and will suggest remedies bolin said after a twoday 
meeting of the group 
cutting down on the use of fossil fuels is likely to be a main 
recommendation in the study to be presented to the un general 
assembly in 1990 he said 
carbon dioxide builds up by burning of fossil fuels like oil 
coal and gas but also through widespread cutting down of trees 
chlorofluorocarbons known mainly as spray propellants also remain 
a factor despite global measures to cut their use bolin said 
the gases are believed to create atmospheric changes that slow 
the escape of heat from earth in a phenomenon known as the 
greenhouse effect 
scientists fear global warming could ultimately lead to more 
frequent extreme weather like frosts and heat waves and changes in 
the sea level and weather patterns 
the group featuring experts from 30 nations was set up in 
november by the world meteorological organization and the un 
environment program 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

