president bush plans to send congress a 116 
trillion budget for fiscal 1990 on thursday that would freeze 
military spending at the level of inflation to help pay for new 
domestic initiatives administration aides said tuesday 
bush himself said his budget would make a strong beginning 
toward the major campaign promises he made during a 1988 campaign in 
which he repeatedly evoked a kinder and gentler nation 
in a major change of emphasis bush will reject former president 
reagans call for a 2 percent rise in defense spending above 
inflation and propose increases in dozens of categories that reagan 
sought to slash said officials who spoke on the condition of 
anonymity 
bushs budget outline a 125page rewrite of the lameduck budget 
reagan submitted last month was pronounced pretty well 
finalized by bush on tuesday 
