<TEXT>
americans obligated themselves to 54 billion 
more in credit than they paid off in december as consumer debt grew 
at an annual rate of 99 percent the government reported tuesday 
the federal reserve board said the december increase followed a 
revised increase of 47 billion in november and a rise of 39 
billion in october 
decembers 99 percent rise in the seasonally adjusted annual 
rate of credit growth was up from an 85 percent rate in november 
and a 72 percent increase in october 
decembers increase matched the 99 percent rise recorded last 
august which was the highest since a 152 percent increase in june 
the december jump was paced by an increase in outstanding auto 
loans while growth in the category of debt that includes credit 
cards slowed from the rapid pace of the preceding two months 
consumer spending is closely watched as a barometer of economic 
health because it accounts for twothirds of the gross national 
product 
economist sandra shaber of the futures group in washington said 
the latest report indicates that consumer finances were healthy in 
december and throughout 1988 
despite the veryoftenheard concerns about consumers 
staggering under a debt burden that really is not the case ms 
shaber said what weve had for two years now is people borrowing 
no more than their income gains were 
auto loans rose by 3 billion in december a 124 percent annual 
rate of growth that followed a 57 percent increase during november 
revolving credit the category that includes credit cards 
increased by 14 billion in december a 91 percent annual rate of 
growth after having risen 211 percent in november 
bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate rose by 
13 billion in december a 95 percent increase in the annual rate 
after having inched up 04 percent in november 
loans for mobile homes decreased by 221 million or a 103 
percent drop after rising 25 percent in the previous month 
overall total consumer debt reached a seasonally adjusted 6673 
billion in december up 89 percent from a year earlier 
