<TEXT>
five central american nations intend to ask 
the united nations on wednesday to send inspectors on surprise 
visits to guarantee that none of the five subverts a neighbor said 
nicaraguas foreign minister 
the minister miguel descoto said tuesday that he and the 
foreign ministers of honduras costa rica guatemala and el salvador 
reached basic agreement on the inspection plan when they met for 
presidential inaugurations in mexico in december and venezuela last 
week 
the ministers agreed that the unarmed civilian inspectors would 
be from spain canada and west germany said a source close to the 
talks who spoke on condition of anonymity 
the five will meet secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar on 
wednesday and descoto said he was optimistic their agreement on 
the plan would hold up 
the presidents of the five nations sent a letter to perez de 
cuellar last month proposing the inspection team he asked for 
details so the foreign ministers decided to meet in new york to 
speed the process said descoto 
he said he could not disclose the details until after all five 
ministers present the proposal and perez de cuellar makes his 
recommendations 
the inspectors would check allegations that one nation was 
harboring rebels from another nation or supporting a rebellion 
which is banned under central american peace accords signed on aug 
7 1987 
on monday evening descoto suggested a small force possibly 10 
inspectors in each of the five capitals 
they would have to have access to every single part of the 
country and they would have to be able to visit every place without 
prior notification descoto said then the element of surprise 
is essential here 
the plan evolved from recommendations made by a joint 
unorganization of american states technical mission that visited 
central america in late 1987 
honduras which blocked accord on the plan at that time by 
refusing to allow inspections of military sites now agrees on a 
plan to ask the secretarygeneral to set up the inspection teams 
said descoto 
honduras is a key us ally where ussupported nicaraguan 
rebels known as contras have bases to launch raids into 
neighboring nicaragua 
the contras have faded as a military force since congress cut off 
funding for weapons some observers believe honduras would like to 
get them out of the country so nicaragua is not tempted to send in 
its superior military forces to mop up the contra bases 
the foreign ministers will hold talks wednesday and thursday to 
prepare for a summit by their five presidents in el salvador next 
monday and tuesday 
the ministers will also try to work out an agreement for 
monitoring the second part of the peace accords calling for 
democratization and political reforms 
descoto said nicaragua would propose an immediate regional open 
door policy in which the five nations would invite in the oas 
united nations amnesty international the international red cross 
and other agencies to monitor human rights 
the interamerican human rights commission would be responsible 
for verifying compliance that human civil and social rights were 
not abused the un working group on forced and involuntary 
disappearances would check on disappeared people and oas and 
un observers would monitor elections in the region under the 
nicaraguasponsored plan 
