<TEXT>
customers besieged banks tuesday 
to acquire us dollars pushing the value of the inflationbattered 
argentine national currency down by 25 percent and intensifying the 
nations economic crisis 
the long lines of depositors waiting to change australs for 
dollars resulted from the central banks decision sunday night to 
restrict dollar sales in an attempt to stabilize the austral and 
hold down inflation 
financial houses were closed monday while the government grappled 
with ways to combat the latin american nations economic travails 
which have forced it to keep interest rates high in order to prevent 
a freefall in the austral 
argentines who gathered outside foreignexchange services early 
tuesday found they had to pay up to 26 australs for the dollar they 
could have purchased for 1759 australs on friday but those who had 
dollars received 21 australs or more compared with 1751 on friday 
during the day the austral kept slipping and by the time 
financial houses closed a dollar fetched 2320 australs it cost 
2350 australs to buy a dollar 
the central bank during the past several months has tightened 
interest rates and taken other steps to support the austral and 
restrain inflation 
but the 68 percent inflation rate in december and 89 percent 
rate in january were worse than expected and suggested to many 
argentines that the governments policies arent working 
inflation in 1988 soared 387 percent 
on monday the government announced it would maintain a 
threetiered exchange rate system the official rate a special 
rate that is 25 percent higher and the black market or free 
rate 
the special rate replaces a rate used to determine how much 
industrial exporters would be paid in australs for their dollars 
farm exporters are required to sell most of the dollars to the 
government at the lower official rate 
argentines who were unhappy with the old system arent happy with 
the new one either 
farm exporters who provide the bulk of argentinas foreign 
exchange earnings grumbled that while the special rate is 
marginally higher than the official rate they still have to sell 
most of their dollars to the central bank at a little more than 14 
australs to the dollar 
businessmen said interest rates which have made borrowing 
prohibitive arent likely to come down even with the exchange rate 
changes 
