<TEXT>
grain and soybean futures prices closed nearly 
unchanged tuesday on the chicago board of trade in a quiet period of 
adjustment after two days of volatile price movement 
new supplyanddemand developments were scarce the agriculture 
department issued a report in the afternoon that said last weeks 
cold temperatures and lack of snow cover may have damaged winter 
wheat in parts of the central and southern plains but the markets 
had anticipated some winter kill 
export demand for us grains and soybeans remained slack which 
weighed on prices but farmer selling was also slow prompting some 
domestic processors to raise their bids on the cash market which 
helped support futures 
analysts said forecasts for more snow this week in the plains and 
the midwest contributed to the generally bearish tone 
at the close wheat was 1 cent lower to cent higher with the 
contract for delivery in march at 426 a bushel corn was cent 
to cent lower with march at 266 a bushel oats were 1 cents to 
2 cents lower with march at 213 a bushel soybeans were 2 cents 
lower to cent higher with march at 753 a bushel 
