<TEXT>
mcdonnell douglas corp and general electric 
corp emerged as the big winners tuesday in an american airlines 
contract for up to 142 planes potentially one of the biggest 
aircraft orders in history 
american said it signed an agreement with mcdonnell douglas to 
acquire at least eight new longrange mdll jetliners with options 
to buy another 42 the airline also took options on 100 md80s a 
smaller plane designed to replace the boeing 727 
the order will make american the first us airline to obtain 
delivery of the md11 a widebody aircraft designed to replace the 
older dc10 company officials told a news conference 
company officials wouldnt disclose the value of the deal but 
industry experts estimate it could total around 7 billion it marks 
a major coup for mcdonnell douglas which has been aggressively 
seeking orders for the md11 in the highstakes aircraft competition 
with boeing co and the airbus industrie consortium of europe 
american also announced that it has signed an agreement with 
general electric to acquire up to 200 cf680c2 engines for use on 
most of its widebody jets including the md11 
american had considered competing engines made by pratt amp whitney 
and britains rollsroyce plc american officials said but decided 
that the ge engines provide more flexibility since they can be used 
on both the md11 and other aircraft 
in a related development tuesday mcdonnell douglas announced 
that in addition to american four other airlines have signed orders 
for new md11s the four carriers air europe of britain aero 
lloyd of west germany zas airline of egypt and finnair the 
national airline of finland have ordered a total of 26 md11s the 
aircraft maker said 
american chose the md11 over boeing cos rival 747400 largely 
because the mcdonnell douglas aircraft will be available sooner 
said robert l crandall americans chairman and president 
the acquisitions by american the nations secondlargest 
carrier come amid rising concern about aging us commercial 
aircraft fleets and whether older planes are less safe 
some airline analysts view the purchases as part of an innovative 
marketing strategy at american to reassure the public about safety 
the new aircraft will replace some older planes in americans 
fleet which is an average of 94 years old compared with 124 
years industrywide 
the agreement gives american great flexibility in planning for 
fleet growth and aircraft replacement in the 1990s and beyond 
crandall said 
one of the most valuable commodities an airline has is the 
confidence of the flying public he said in addition to upgrading 
its fleet american also is paying strict attention to inspecting 
and maintaining its older aircraft he noted 
as a result of the new acquisitions americans fleet will be the 
youngest in the us airline industry by the end of 1991 crandall 
said 
american plans to spend around 105 billion through the end of 
1993 to modernize its fleet donald j carty the airlines senior 
vice president for planning and finance told the news conference 
