<TEXT>
a judge temporarily barred a national pennystock 
brokerage house from soliciting new business in new york state 
tuesday after the state attorney general said there was evidence it 
had defrauded millions of dollars from thousands of investors 
attorney general robert abrams said records showed that power 
securities corp of las vegas participated in a massive fraud and 
swindle that involved manipulating stock prices creating 
artificial markets and marking up stock prices by 100 percent or 
more 
state supreme court justice jawn a sandifer issued a temporary 
restraining order barring power securities from soliciting new 
business in or from the state the judge also ordered the company to 
provide documents and sworn testimony 
power securities issued a statement saying it would cooperate 
with the inquiry and present relevant information at a feb 22 
hearing however the statement said the company intends to 
vigorously oppose the existing restraining order and any 
restrictions order and any restrictions on its business activities 
penny stocks are inexpensive securities sold over the counter 
they are not listed on any major stock exchanges 
power securiti 62 of denver 
it employs 106 salespeople in four offices in new york state and 
400 more around the country are registered to solcompany grew 20fold in 
just over 18 
months and that the company claimed it had grown 50fold he said 
some brokers made 100000 a month 
under state securities law the attorney general can apply for a 
restraining order if he shows that investors are in danger of being 
defrauded 
abrams said deception and fraudulent conduct are at the very 
heart of their business enterprise he said the temporary order 
would help the state gather information that could lead to a lawsuit 
to permanently bar the company from doing business in the state 
according to an affidavit signed by assistant attorney general 
william h mohr salespeople used coordinated buyandsell campaigns 
to create an artificial intramural market and make a profit 
salespeople would tell one group of investors to sell while telling 
another group to buy he said 
abrams cited as an example the alleged manipulation of genexus 
international inc stock from oct 19 to oct 25 1988 
salespeople allegedly convinced one group of investors to sell 82 
million shares back to power for 22 cents per share or less and 
within five days resold the shares to another group for 3 cents a 
share leaving a profit of at least 650000 for power abrams said 
state and federal authorities have recently focused on potential 
fraud in penny stock deals which offer the illusion of quick 
profits for investors and involve littleknown companies 
abrams said the penny stock market is ripe for fraud companies 
like power securities find it an easy market in which to use lies 
and deception to enrich themselves 
mohrs affidavit was based partly on records filed with the state 
to register salespeople tape recordings of phone sales pitches 
statements and records of companies whose stocks are sold by power 
and interviews with former salespeople and disgruntled investors 
the affidavit also said there was evidence that power marked up 
the price of shares it bought from other brokers by as much as 100 
percent and resold them without disclosing the original price 
the judges order also froze the assets of star publications inc 
of colorado and sought records of its principals abrams charged 
that in conjunction with power securities star fraudulently claimed 
it had marketing rights to a folding disposable razor and claimed 
the defense department was about to buy large quantities of them 
</TEXT>
