<TEXT>
holly farms corps board of directors on 
tuesday recommended the companys stockholders approve a merger 
agreement with conagra inc instead of a rival proposal from tyson 
foods inc 
the board said conagras stockswap proposal was substantially 
equal to a tyson proposal to pay 6350 per share if holly farms 
agreed to a merger and had less strings attached tyson also has an 
outstanding 60 a share hostile cash tender offer for holly farms 
the company said a stockholders meeting would be convened as soon 
as possible to vote on a merger with conagra 
conagras deal has been valued at about 106 billion and tysons 
109 billion 
the holly farms board said there were reasons to doubt that a 
deal with tyson could be completed 
this was due to the prospect of protracted litigation between 
conagra and tyson foods the company said 
the holly farms board said an opinion from investment banker 
morgan stanley amp co said the terms of the conagra agreement were 
fair to hollys stockholders 
holly farms shares lost 12 cents to close at 6162 in 
consolidated new york stock exchange trading 
tyson on monday extended its cash tender offer for the company 
for another week officials for the company deferred calls tuesday 
to attorneys in new york who were not available for comment 
conagra an omaha nebbased food and poultry processor and 
tyson of springdale ark have been seeking holly farms for months 
holly based in memphis tenn had intended to merge with 
conagra but later encouraged both suitors to up their offers in 
order to maximize the gain for shareholders in the event of a sale 
the boards announcement was the second major setback to tyson in 
the past several days last monday a federal judge barred tyson 
from issuing false or misleading information about its takeover 
offers for holly farms 
the company since its board meeting of jan 20 had invited 
tyson and conagra to improve the terms of their respective 
proposals the holly statement said conagra had made no 
changes tyson had added a condition to theirs and that along with 
the prospect of litigation between tyson and conagra had led the 
board to conclude that their concerns over the tyson proposal were 
even more acute than before 
holly spokesman ted bailey said the company would mail statements 
to shareholders soon seeking their approval of the conagra deal 
</TEXT>
